{
  "doc_id": "49994",
  "text": "Forkhead box protein O3a (FoxO3a), which belongs to the Forkhead transcription factors of the FoxO subfamily (FoxOs), is reported to be involved in cell cycle arrest [CITATION_1] , apoptosis [CITATION_2] , and the oxidative stress response (14, [CITATION_3] . Recently, Greer et al. [CITATION_4] showed that FoxO3a, but not FoxO1, is directly phosphorylated and activated by AMPK in vitro. FoxO3a is reported to positively regulate mitochondria-related genes, such as uncoupling proteins, in mouse embryonic fibroblasts, suggesting that the direct regulation of FoxO3a by AMPK plays a crucial role in the control of the cellular energy balance. The phosphorylation of FoxO3a by AMPK was also identified in C2C12 myotubes [CITATION_5] , aortic vascular endothelial cells [CITATION_6] , and A549 lung cancer cells [CITATION_7] . However, the role of the AMPK/FoxO3a pathway in hepatocytes, an important target of metformin, remains unknown.",
